      "solution": "s = input()\neven_to_char = {'0': 'A', '2': 'C', '4': 'E', '6': 'G', '8': 'I'}\nodd_digits = [c for c in s if c not in even_to_char][::-1]\nresult = [even_to_char[c] if c in even_to_char else odd_digits.pop(0) for c in s]\nprint(''.join(result))",
      "statement": "You are trying to crack a digital keypad lock that displays a sequence of numbers. The lock mechanism works in a specific way: for each digit in the sequence, you have to change it based on specific rules.\n\nGiven a sequence of digits (0-9), you need to:\n\n(1) Change even digits ({{0}}, {{2}}, {{4}}, {{6}}, {{8}}) to their corresponding position in the alphabet ({{0}} becomes {{A}}, {{2}} becomes {{C}}, etc.).\n(2) Reverse the positions of the odd digits  ({{1}}, {{3}}, {{5}}, {{7}}, {{9}}) in the sequence and keep them as numbers.\n\nThe final result is a mix of letters and digits where:\n\nEven digits are replaced by corresponding alphabet letters based on position.\nOdd digits are reversed and remain numbers.",
